    "narrative": "Today\u2019s slate for Ghost Ride the WHIP centers on maximizing efficiency against softer matchups, with **Corbin Carroll** leading the way as our strongest play (81.24). Despite drawing a veteran arm in Max Scherzer, **Corbin Carroll**\u2019s projected output is buoyed by a favorable batting order (#2) and strong dynamic platoon indicators. We are also leaning heavily into the matchup against Fedde; **Tyler Soderstrom** (76.91) stands out as an elite start, benefiting from a high-run-environment park and the opposing pitcher's poor xERA, while **Max Muncy** (64.71) provides secondary stability in that same contest. **James Wood** (73.32) remains a high-floor staple at the top of the lineup, where his ability to steal bags\u2014the scarcest commodity in our pursuit\u2014is bolstered by favorable conditions despite facing a competent catcher in Houser.\n\nTactical adjustments highlight the importance of park and platoon variables today. **Vinnie Pasquantino** (69.30) earns a solid start at UTIL, leveraging a significant dynamic platoon advantage against Warren, while **Mickey Moniak** (64.11) sees his score spike thanks to an ideal park factor that outweighs the risk of facing Sheehan. Conversely, we have benched **Seiya Suzuki** (51.44), who sits just outside our start threshold; while his raw talent is clear, his negative BvP history and the daunting matchup against Peralta made him the most difficult omission of the day. We are monitoring **Luis Campusano**, whose score (51.88) is precarious; should the official lineup slot him further down the order or if weather shifts impact the wind-in factor at the stadium, he remains our most volatile asset. Keep an eye on **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (57.47); the combination of a wind-in warning and a difficult platoon split against Cameron keeps him in the marginal range, though his speed profile keeps him on the field.",
